PROJECT NARRATIVE. This project asks how communities decide which goods should
be insulated from market allocation, and what follows for policy when those
decisions conflict. The question matters because the boundary between what may
be bought and sold is not fixed by economics alone; it is drawn and redrawn
through argument, and the terms of that argument are poorly understood.

SIGNIFICANCE. Scholars have catalogued the goods societies treat as
market-inalienable, but the cataloguing has outrun the explanation. We do not
have a good account of why the line falls where it does, or of how it moves.
The prevailing explanations appeal either to efficiency or to a list of sacred
values, and neither travels well: efficiency cannot say why some efficient
trades are forbidden, and the appeal to sacred values restates the boundary it
was meant to explain. This project develops and tests an alternative, on which
the boundary tracks a community's judgment about which relationships a market in
the good would corrupt.

APPROACH. We combine conceptual analysis with two empirical components. The
conceptual work specifies the corruption claim precisely enough to be tested,
distinguishing it from the efficiency and sacred-value accounts. The first
empirical component is a survey experiment that varies the relationship a
proposed market would affect and measures support for prohibition. The second
is a historical analysis of three cases in which a market boundary shifted,
tracing the arguments that accompanied the shift. The components are designed to
converge: if the corruption account is right, the survey should show that
relationship-framing moves support, and the histories should show
corruption-style arguments doing the work at the moments of change.

OBJECTIONS AND RESPONSES. One objection holds that corruption is too vague to
explain anything. We answer by operationalizing it as a measurable judgment
about relationship change, which the survey can move. A second objection holds
that we have merely relabeled the sacred-value account. We distinguish the two:
sacred-value accounts forbid trade in the good as such, while the corruption
account forbids it only where a market would change a relationship for the
worse, and the cases come apart.

OUTCOMES. The project will yield a tested account of market boundaries and a
framework usable by policymakers who must decide, under disagreement, which
goods to wall off from exchange.
